chunks: 1951 CONVENTION RELATING TO THE STATUS OF REFUGEES AND 1967 PROTOCOL — KEY PROVISIONS PREAMBLE The High Contracting Parties, considering that the Charter of the United Nations and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights have affirmed the principle that human beings shall enjoy fundamental rights and freedoms without discrimination, and considering that the United Nations has manifested its profound concern for refugees, agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 — DEFINITION OF THE TERM "REFUGEE" A. For the purposes of the present Convention, the term "refugee" shall apply to any person who: (2) As a result of events occurring before 1 January 1951 and owing to a well-founded fear of being persecuted for reasons of race, religion, nationality, membership of a particular

social group or political opinion, is outside the country of his nationality and is unable or, owing to such fear, is unwilling to avail himself of the protection of that country; or who, not having a nationality and being outside the country of his former habitual residence, is unable or, owing to such fear, is unwilling to return to it. The 1967 Protocol removed the dateline restriction, making the Convention universally applicable. A refugee under current law is any person with a well-founded fear of persecution for reasons of race, religion, nationality, membership of a particular social group, or political opinion, who is outside their country of nationality and unable or unwilling to return. B. The term "refugee" shall cease

to apply when the person: (1) has voluntarily re-availed themselves of the protection of the country of their nationality; (2) has voluntarily reacquired their lost nationality; (3) has acquired a new nationality and enjoys protection of that country; (4) has voluntarily re-established themselves in the country which they left out of fear of persecution; (5) can no longer refuse to avail themselves of the protection of their country because the circumstances in connection with which they have been recognized as a refugee have ceased to exist; (6) being stateless, is able to return to their country of former habitual residence. ARTICLE 3 — NON-DISCRIMINATION The Contracting States shall apply the provisions of this Convention to refugees without discrimination as to

race, religion, or country of origin. ARTICLE 4 — RELIGION The Contracting States shall accord to refugees within their territories treatment at least as favorable as that accorded to their nationals with respect to freedom to practice their religion and freedom as regards the religious education of their children. ARTICLE 12 — PERSONAL STATUS The personal status of a refugee shall be governed by the law of the country of his domicile or, if he has no domicile, by the law of the country of his residence. ARTICLE 13 — MOVABLE AND IMMOVABLE PROPERTY The Contracting States shall accord to a refugee treatment as favorable as possible and, in any event, not less favorable than that accorded to aliens generally

in the same circumstances, as regards the acquisition of movable and immovable property and other rights pertaining thereto, and to leases and other contracts relating to movable and immovable property. ARTICLE 17 — WAGE-EARNING EMPLOYMENT The Contracting States shall accord to refugees lawfully staying in their territory the most favorable treatment accorded to nationals of a foreign country in the same circumstances, as regards the right to engage in wage-earning employment. ARTICLE 18 — SELF-EMPLOYMENT The Contracting States shall accord to a refugee lawfully in their territory treatment as favorable as possible and, in any event, not less favorable than that accorded to aliens generally in the same circumstances, with respect to the right to engage on his own account

in agriculture, industry, handicrafts and commerce and to establish commercial and industrial companies. ARTICLE 22 — PUBLIC EDUCATION The Contracting States shall accord to refugees the same treatment as is accorded to nationals with respect to elementary education. ARTICLE 23 — PUBLIC RELIEF The Contracting States shall accord to refugees lawfully staying in their territory the same treatment with respect to public relief and assistance as is accorded to their nationals. ARTICLE 24 — LABOUR LEGISLATION AND SOCIAL SECURITY The Contracting States shall accord to refugees lawfully staying in their territory the same treatment as is accorded to nationals in respect of labor legislation and social security (insurance for accidents, occupational disease, maternity, illness, disability, old age, death, unemployment, family

responsibilities, and other contingencies covered by national legislation). ARTICLE 26 — FREEDOM OF MOVEMENT Each Contracting State shall accord to refugees lawfully in its territory the right to choose their place of residence and to move freely within its territory subject to any regulations applicable to aliens generally in the same circumstances. ARTICLE 27 — IDENTITY PAPERS The Contracting States shall issue identity papers to any refugee in their territory who does not possess a valid travel document. ARTICLE 28 — TRAVEL DOCUMENTS The Contracting States shall issue to refugees lawfully staying in their territory travel documents for the purpose of travel outside their territory, unless compelling reasons of national security or public order otherwise require. The document shall be

valid for as long a period as possible and for at least one year. ARTICLE 31 — REFUGEES UNLAWFULLY IN THE COUNTRY OF REFUGE The Contracting States shall not impose penalties, on account of their illegal entry or presence, on refugees who, coming directly from a territory where their life or freedom was threatened in the sense of Article 1, enter or are present in their territory without authorization, provided they present themselves without delay to the authorities and show good cause for their illegal entry or presence. ARTICLE 32 — EXPULSION The Contracting States shall not expel a refugee lawfully in their territory save on grounds of national security or public order. The expulsion of such a refugee shall

be only in pursuance of a decision reached in accordance with due process of law. The refugee shall be allowed to submit evidence to clear themselves, to appeal to and be represented before a competent authority. ARTICLE 33 — NON-REFOULEMENT (PROHIBITION OF EXPULSION OR RETURN) No Contracting State shall expel or return ("refouler") a refugee in any manner whatsoever to the frontiers of territories where his life or freedom would be threatened on account of his race, religion, nationality, membership of a particular social group or political opinion. The benefit of this provision may not, however, be claimed by a refugee whom there are reasonable grounds for regarding as a danger to the security of the country in which he

is, or who, having been convicted by a final judgment of a particularly serious crime, constitutes a danger to the community of that country. NON-REFOULEMENT is the cornerstone of international refugee protection. It is considered a jus cogens norm of customary international law, binding even on states that have not signed the Convention. It prohibits returning any person to a place where they face a real risk of serious harm, including torture, cruel treatment, or persecution. ARTICLE 34 — NATURALIZATION The Contracting States shall as far as possible facilitate the assimilation and naturalization of refugees. They shall in particular make every effort to expedite naturalization proceedings and to reduce as far as possible the charges and costs of such proceedings.

GROUNDS FOR PERSECUTION (Article 1A(2) — Expanded Interpretation) Race: Includes ethnicity and ancestry. Persecution on grounds of race includes measures directed against members of a racial group, or persons perceived to belong to a racial group. Religion: Includes theistic, non-theistic, and atheistic beliefs, as well as freedom to change religion, and freedom to practice religion alone or in community. Nationality: Encompasses citizenship, ethnicity, language, and cultural identity. Political Opinion: Includes any opinion on any matter in which the machinery of the State, government, or society may be engaged. An applicant need not have expressed their political opinion where there is a risk of persecution based on imputed political opinion. Particular Social Group: A group of persons who share a common

characteristic other than their risk of persecution, or who are perceived as a group by society. The characteristic must be innate, unchangeable, or so fundamental to identity or conscience that the person should not be required to renounce it. Examples include: LGBTQ+ individuals, women subjected to gender-based violence, victims of domestic violence, former members of military, clan or family associations, landowners in land reform contexts. WELL-FOUNDED FEAR — STANDARD OF PROOF The applicant must demonstrate that there is a reasonable possibility (not certainty) of persecution. Both subjective fear (the applicant genuinely fears persecution) and objective basis (the fear is reasonable in light of country conditions) must be established. The standard is significantly lower than a preponderance of evidence — even
a 10% chance of persecution may suffice.

ASYLUM ELIGIBILITY GUIDELINES (Based on 1951 Convention) 1. WELL-FOUNDED FEAR: The applicant must demonstrate a subjective fear of persecution that is objectively reasonable. 2. PERSECUTION: Serious harm or human rights violations, often by the government or groups the government cannot/will not control. 3. PROTECTED GROUNDS: Persecution must be on account of: - Race - Religion - Nationality - Membership in a particular social group (PSG) - Political opinion 4. FIRM RESETTLEMENT: If an applicant has firmly resettled in another country before arriving in the US, they may be ineligible. 5. ONE-YEAR FILING DEADLINE: Asylum applications must generally be filed within one year of arrival in the US. 6. CREDIBILITY: The applicant's testimony must be consistent, detailed, and plausible.

PRACTICAL GUIDE TO THE ASYLUM PROCESS Frequently Asked Questions for Asylum Seekers in the United States Q: WHAT DOCUMENTS DO I NEED TO APPLY FOR ASYLUM? You should gather as many of the following as possible, though not all are required: - Identity documents: passport, national ID card, birth certificate - Evidence of persecution: police reports, hospital/medical records, photographs, videos, news articles, witness statements - Country condition evidence: human rights reports from Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, US State Department Country Reports on Human Rights Practices, Freedom House reports, UNHCR Country of Origin Information - Personal statement: A detailed written account of your persecution or fear of persecution (this is submitted with Form I-589 or presented to the immigration judge)

- Expert reports: psychological evaluations documenting trauma; country expert declarations - Proof of membership in a persecuted group: church membership, party membership cards, certificates, letters from organizations - Documents showing family ties if claiming derivative asylum Q: HOW DO I APPLY FOR ASYLUM? Affirmative Process: If you are not in removal proceedings, file Form I-589 (Application for Asylum and Withholding of Removal) directly with USCIS. There is no filing fee for Form I-589. Defensive Process: If you are in removal proceedings before an Immigration Judge, you must file the I-589 with the Immigration Court before the deadline set by the judge. You must file within one year of arrival unless you qualify for an exception. Q: WHAT HAPPENS AFTER I

FILE MY ASYLUM APPLICATION? 1. You will receive a receipt notice confirming your application was filed. 2. You will be scheduled for a biometrics appointment (fingerprints, photo) at an ASC. 3. For affirmative applications: USCIS will schedule an interview with an asylum officer (currently experiencing long delays — often 2 or more years). 4. You may apply for an Employment Authorization Document (EAD) 150 days after filing. Q: CAN I WORK WHILE MY ASYLUM CASE IS PENDING? Yes. You must wait 180 days after filing a complete asylum application before you are eligible to receive work authorization. You apply for work authorization using Form I-765. Once issued, you can legally work in the United States while your case is pending.

Your employer can verify your work authorization using E-Verify. Q: WHAT IS THE CREDIBLE FEAR INTERVIEW? If you are apprehended at or near the border and placed in expedited removal proceedings, a USCIS asylum officer will conduct a credible fear interview to determine if you have a credible fear of persecution or torture. You must express a fear of return and demonstrate a significant possibility of establishing eligibility for asylum. If you pass the credible fear screening, you are referred to Immigration Court for full asylum proceedings. Q: WHAT IF MY ASYLUM APPLICATION IS DENIED? If denied by an asylum officer (affirmative): Your case is referred to an Immigration Judge for a full de novo hearing. The denial by the

asylum officer does not bind the judge. If denied by an Immigration Judge: You have 30 days to file a Notice of Appeal with the Board of Immigration Appeals (BIA). The denial does not take effect while the appeal is pending. If denied by the BIA: You have 30 days to file a Petition for Review with the federal Circuit Court of Appeals. You may request a stay of removal. If all appeals are exhausted: You may be removed, but you may still apply for a Motion to Reopen if circumstances change, or explore other immigration relief. Q: WHAT IS WITHHOLDING OF REMOVAL AND HOW IS IT DIFFERENT FROM ASYLUM? Withholding of removal (INA § 241(b)(3)) prevents the government from

removing you to a specific country where your life or freedom would be threatened. Key differences: - Higher standard: You must show it is "more likely than not" (51%+) you will be persecuted — compared to only a reasonable possibility for asylum - No path to permanent residence or citizenship - No derivative protection for family members - Not subject to one-year filing deadline - Available even if bars to asylum apply (except persecution, danger to national security, or particularly serious crime) Q: WHAT PROTECTION IS AVAILABLE UNDER THE CONVENTION AGAINST TORTURE (CAT)? Even if you do not qualify for asylum or withholding of removal, you may be protected under the Convention Against Torture if you can show it is

more likely than not that you would be tortured in the country of removal, and that torture would be inflicted by or with the acquiescence of a government official. CAT protection is available to anyone, including those with serious criminal convictions that bar asylum. Q: WHAT ARE MY RIGHTS WHILE MY ASYLUM CASE IS PENDING? - Right to remain in the United States while your case is pending (no removal while case is active) - Right to a lawyer (at no expense to the government) - Right to an interpreter in immigration court proceedings - Right to present evidence and witnesses - Right to appeal a denial - Right to apply for work authorization after 150 days - Right to

protection from refoulement Q: CAN MY FAMILY MEMBERS ALSO GET ASYLUM? Yes. If you are granted asylum, your spouse and unmarried children under 21 may be included in your grant of asylum as derivative asylees if they are in the United States. You can also file Form I-730 (Refugee/Asylee Relative Petition) to bring qualifying family members to the United States within two years of your asylum grant. Derivative asylees receive the same rights as principal asylees. Q: WHAT HAPPENS AFTER I AM GRANTED ASYLUM? - You receive an I-94 showing asylee status - You are authorized to work immediately upon the grant - You may receive a Form I-730 to petition for qualifying family members - After one year from

being granted asylum, you may apply for permanent residence (Green Card) using Form I-485 - After five years as a permanent resident (four years for asylees, since one year of asylee status counts toward the residency requirement), you may apply for US citizenship if other requirements are met Q: WHAT IF I CANNOT AFFORD A LAWYER? Asylum seekers have the right to hire an attorney but there is no right to a free government-appointed attorney in immigration proceedings. However, many resources exist: - UNHCR registered legal partners - Immigration Legal Services programs (Catholic Charities, IRC, Lutheran Immigration and Refugee Service, RAICES, CLINIC, AILA Pro Bono programs) - Law school immigration clinics (provide free or low-cost services) - Legal aid organizations

in your city or state - EOIR's List of Free Legal Service Providers (available at all immigration courts) - Accredited representatives of Board of Immigration Appeals-recognized organizations Q: WHAT HAPPENS IF I MISS MY ASYLUM INTERVIEW OR COURT HEARING? Failing to appear for a USCIS asylum interview will result in your case being dismissed. Failing to appear for an Immigration Court hearing will result in an order of removal being issued in absentia. You must notify USCIS or the court of any change of address (Form AR-11 and Form EOIR-33) within 5 days of moving. If you have a good reason for missing a hearing, you may file a Motion to Reopen. Q: WHAT IS TEMPORARY PROTECTED STATUS (TPS)? TPS

is a temporary immigration status granted to eligible nationals from designated countries experiencing armed conflict, natural disaster, or other extraordinary conditions. TPS provides protection from removal and work authorization but is not a path to permanent residence. TPS is periodically renewed by the Secretary of Homeland Security and can be terminated. Currently designated countries include: Afghanistan, Burma, Cameroon, El Salvador, Ethiopia, Haiti, Honduras, Nepal, Nicaragua, Somalia, South Sudan, Sudan, Syria, Ukraine, Venezuela, and Yemen, among others. Q: WHAT IS DEFERRED ACTION AND DACA? Deferred Action is an exercise of prosecutorial discretion where DHS decides not to pursue removal of an individual for a set period, often renewed annually. DACA (Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals) protects certain individuals who came to

the US as children from removal and provides work authorization, but does not provide legal status or a path to permanent residence. DACA recipients came to the US before age 16 and before June 15, 2007, and meet education and criminal history requirements. Q: HOW CAN I CHECK MY CASE STATUS? USCIS cases: Check online at uscis.gov/case-status using your receipt number Immigration Court cases: Call the automated hotline at 1-800-898-7180 or check at acis.eoir.justice.gov BIA cases: Check at eoir.justice.gov Q: WHAT COUNTRY CONDITIONS REPORTS CAN I USE TO SUPPORT MY CASE? The following authoritative sources are commonly cited: - US Department of State Country Reports on Human Rights Practices (state.gov) - UNHCR Country of Origin Information and Eligibility Guidelines (unhcr.org)

- Amnesty International Annual Report (amnesty.org) - Human Rights Watch World Report (hrw.org) - Freedom House Freedom in the World Report (freedomhouse.org) - Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada (IRB) country information (canada.ca) - EOIR Immigration Court's Virtual Law Library country condition materials

UNHCR GUIDELINES ON INTERNATIONAL PROTECTION United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees UNHCR MANDATE AND ROLE The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) is mandated by the United Nations General Assembly to lead and coordinate international action for the worldwide protection of refugees and the resolution of refugee problems. UNHCR's primary purpose is to safeguard the rights and well-being of refugees. UNHCR pursues this mission through international protection, emergency assistance, durable solutions, and advocacy. UNHCR DEFINITION OF A REFUGEE (Broader Mandate) In addition to the 1951 Convention definition, UNHCR's mandate encompasses persons outside their country who are unable or unwilling to return due to serious and indiscriminate threats to life, physical

integrity or freedom resulting from generalized violence or events seriously disturbing public order (OAU Convention, Cartagena Declaration). This broader definition applies in many African and Latin American countries. THE THREE DURABLE SOLUTIONS 1. VOLUNTARY REPATRIATION Voluntary repatriation is the return of refugees to their country of origin in safety and dignity. UNHCR facilitates voluntary repatriation when conditions in the country of origin have improved sufficiently to make return possible. Repatriation must be voluntary — refugees cannot be forced to return. UNHCR assists with transportation, reintegration packages, and monitoring. 2. LOCAL INTEGRATION Local integration allows refugees to settle permanently in the country of asylum. This involves granting refugees the right to remain, to work, to access social services, and eventually to

adjust to permanent residence or citizenship. It is a long-term solution requiring strong host government commitment. 3. RESETTLEMENT Resettlement is the transfer of refugees from the country of asylum to a third country that has agreed to admit them as refugees with permanent residence status. UNHCR refers refugees for resettlement when the refugee faces particular vulnerabilities. In 2023, approximately 2.4 million refugees were in need of resettlement globally, but only around 100,000 resettlement places were made available by states each year. RESETTLEMENT CRITERIA — UNHCR UNHCR considers refugees for resettlement referral on the following grounds: - Legal and physical protection needs (including risk of refoulement or arbitrary detention) - Survivors of violence and torture - Medical needs that cannot be

treated in the country of asylum - Women and girls at risk (gender-based violence, trafficking, sexual exploitation) - Family reunification - Children and adolescents at risk (unaccompanied or separated children, child labor, child marriage) - Lack of foreseeable alternative durable solutions UNHCR REFUGEE STATUS DETERMINATION (RSD) In countries where the national government does not conduct refugee status determination, UNHCR conducts RSD on behalf of the state. UNHCR RSD involves: - Registration of asylum seekers - Assessment of whether the applicant meets the refugee definition - Consideration of exclusion clauses (Articles 1C, 1D, 1E, 1F of the 1951 Convention) - Decision and notification - Right to appeal a negative decision STATELESS PERSONS In addition to refugees, UNHCR is mandated to prevent

and reduce statelessness and to protect stateless persons. A stateless person is someone who is not considered a national by any State under the operation of its law. Stateless persons may be at risk of detention, inability to register births, marriages, or deaths, lack of access to education, healthcare, employment, and freedom of movement. Stateless persons may also qualify for refugee protection if they fear persecution. PROTECTION FOR SPECIFIC GROUPS Women and Girls: Gender-based persecution includes sexual violence, female genital mutilation (FGM/C), forced marriage, honor crimes, and trafficking. UNHCR Guidelines on International Protection No. 1 (Gender-Related Persecution) provides that women persecuted for transgressing social norms may qualify under "particular social group." LGBTIQ+ Persons: UNHCR recognizes LGBTIQ+ persons as members of

a "particular social group" for refugee protection purposes. Persecution based on sexual orientation or gender identity, including criminalization of same-sex conduct and threats of violence, supports asylum claims. Unaccompanied and Separated Children: UNHCR Guidelines on International Protection No. 8 (Child Asylum Claims) emphasizes child-sensitive procedures, best interests determination, and appointed guardians. Children may have independent international protection needs. Victims of Trafficking: Victims of human trafficking may qualify for refugee protection if they have been trafficked for reasons related to a protected ground or if they fear retaliation, re-trafficking, or persecution by state actors upon return. Religious Minorities: Persecution of religious minorities includes prohibitions on worship or religious instruction, violence against religious communities, and forced conversion. The right to freedom of

religion includes the right to change religion and to practice religion publicly. Ethnic and Cultural Minorities: Persecution of ethnic minorities includes ethnic cleansing, forced assimilation, denial of language rights, and systematic discrimination amounting to persecution. UNHCR GUIDANCE ON NON-REFOULEMENT Non-refoulement applies to everyone who might be a refugee, including asylum seekers whose status has not been formally determined. States must not return anyone to a risk of serious harm, including torture and cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment or punishment (as protected under CAT and ICCPR Article 7). Non-refoulement applies at borders, in international waters, and in extraterritorial zones. UNHCR GUIDANCE ON DETENTION The detention of asylum seekers and refugees is inherently undesirable. Detention must be used only as a last

resort, must be proportionate, and must not be punitive. Asylum seekers should not be detained solely for the purpose of determining immigration status. Alternatives to detention must be considered first. UNHCR advocates for community-based alternatives to detention (ATD) programs. UNHCR GLOBAL TRENDS As of 2023, there were approximately 110 million forcibly displaced people worldwide, including 36.4 million refugees under UNHCR's mandate, 5.9 million Palestine refugees under UNRWA's mandate, 62.5 million internally displaced persons (IDPs), and 5.2 million asylum seekers. The largest refugee populations originate from Syria, Ukraine, Afghanistan, South Sudan, and Myanmar. UNHCR COUNTRY OF ORIGIN INFORMATION (COI) UNHCR publishes country guidance notes, eligibility guidelines, and country of origin information for many countries of origin of refugees. These documents are

frequently used by immigration courts and asylum officers to assess country conditions. They cover: security situation, human rights violations, persecution of specific groups, government protection, and internal relocation options. ACCESS TO ASYLUM States must provide access to a fair and efficient asylum procedure. Asylum seekers must be informed of their rights. Interpreters must be provided. Applications must be individually assessed. Decisions must be reasoned and subject to appeal. Asylum seekers must be protected from refoulement while their claim is pending. Effective access to legal assistance must be facilitated. FAIR HEARING PRINCIPLES - The applicant must have adequate time and opportunity to prepare and present their claim - The applicant must be interviewed by a trained and impartial decision-maker - An

interpreter must be provided in a language the applicant understands - Confidentiality must be maintained — authorities from the country of origin must not be informed of the asylum application - The applicant must not be discriminated against on grounds of gender, age, disability, sexuality, or other protected characteristics - A negative decision must be explained in full, with an effective right of appeal before an independent body INTERNATIONAL PROTECTION OBLIGATIONS States that have ratified the 1951 Refugee Convention and its 1967 Protocol are bound to protect refugees within their territory. As of 2024, 149 states have ratified the 1951 Convention. Key obligations include: non-refoulement, non-penalization for illegal entry, provision of identity documents, access to courts, freedom of movement, right
to work, access to education, and access to social security.

UNITED STATES ASYLUM LAW — COMPREHENSIVE GUIDE Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) §§ 101(a)(42), 208, 241(b)(3) 8 U.S.C. §§ 1101, 1158, 1231 DEFINITION OF REFUGEE (INA § 101(a)(42)) Under U.S. law, a refugee is any person who is outside their country of nationality and unable or unwilling to return because of persecution or a well-founded fear of persecution on account of race, religion, nationality, membership in a particular social group, or political opinion. Persons who ordered, incited, assisted, or participated in persecution of others do not qualify. WHO CAN APPLY FOR ASYLUM Any person physically present in the United States, regardless of immigration status, may apply for asylum. This includes persons who entered without authorization, persons on valid visas, students,

workers, and tourists. Persons who are in expedited removal proceedings may seek asylum in a credible fear interview. Unaccompanied alien children have special procedural protections and their claims are adjudicated by USCIS regardless of whether they are in removal proceedings. THE ONE-YEAR FILING DEADLINE Asylum applications must generally be filed within one year of the applicant's last arrival in the United States (INA § 208(a)(2)(B)). Exceptions exist for: - Changed circumstances materially affecting eligibility (e.g., changed country conditions, change in law, change in applicant's circumstances including marriage, birth of child, conversion to a new religion) - Extraordinary circumstances relating to the delay (serious illness, legal disability, ineffective assistance of prior counsel, maintained lawful immigration status until recently) The applicant bears

the burden of proof for establishing an exception to the one-year bar. TWO PATHWAYS TO ASYLUM IN THE UNITED STATES 1. AFFIRMATIVE ASYLUM (not in removal proceedings) The applicant files Form I-589 (Application for Asylum and Withholding of Removal) with USCIS. An asylum officer conducts a non-adversarial interview. If approved, the applicant is granted asylum. If not approved and the applicant is not in lawful status, the case is referred to an Immigration Judge in removal proceedings for a de novo review. 2. DEFENSIVE ASYLUM (in removal proceedings before Immigration Court) The applicant raises asylum as a defense to removal before an Immigration Judge (IJ) in the Executive Office for Immigration Review (EOIR). The asylum application is reviewed in an

adversarial hearing with a DHS attorney representing the government. If denied by the IJ, the applicant may appeal to the Board of Immigration Appeals (BIA). If the BIA denies, the applicant may petition for review in the applicable federal Court of Appeals. ELIGIBILITY REQUIREMENTS — DETAILED Nexus Requirement: The persecution must be "on account of" one of the five protected grounds. The protected ground need not be the sole reason for persecution but must be "at least one central reason." Mixed motives are permissible. Persecution by Whom: Persecution may be carried out by government actors or by private individuals or groups that the government is unable or unwilling to control. Domestic violence, gang violence, and persecution by criminal organizations may

qualify if the government is unable or unwilling to protect the victim. Severity of Harm: Persecution is more than mere harassment or discrimination. It encompasses threats to life, physical injury, imprisonment without due process, arbitrary arrest, severe restriction of liberty, denial of basic necessities of life, significant economic deprivation, and cumulative lesser harms. Internal Relocation: Even if the applicant faces persecution in one part of their country, asylum may be denied if the applicant can reasonably relocate within the country to avoid persecution. The burden shifts to the government to show internal relocation is reasonable if the persecution is by a government actor. BURDEN OF PROOF The applicant bears the burden of establishing eligibility by a preponderance of the evidence.

An applicant's credible testimony alone may be sufficient to meet this burden even without corroborating evidence (REAL ID Act, INA § 208(b)(1)(B)(ii)). CREDIBILITY DETERMINATION Immigration judges assess credibility based on: demeanor and candor; internal consistency of statements; consistency with prior statements and country condition evidence; accuracy of country condition information; and sufficiency of corroboration when reasonably available. An adverse credibility finding does not automatically require denial if the applicant provides sufficient corroboration. BARS TO ASYLUM The following persons are ineligible for asylum: - Persons who persecuted others on account of a protected ground - Persons convicted of a "particularly serious crime" (aggravated felony by statute; other crimes require case-by-case analysis of nature, circumstances, and potential danger) - Persons who committed

a "serious non-political crime" outside the US prior to arrival - Persons who pose a danger to US national security - Persons firmly resettled in a third country prior to arriving in the US - Persons who filed an application for protection in a safe third country (if Safe Third Country Agreement applies, e.g., US-Canada) WITHHOLDING OF REMOVAL (INA § 241(b)(3)) Even if asylum is denied (due to a bar or procedural failure), an applicant may still be entitled to withholding of removal, which prohibits the government from removing the applicant to a country where their life or freedom would be threatened. The standard is higher than asylum: applicant must show it is "more likely than not" that they will

be persecuted. Withholding does not provide a path to permanent residence. CONVENTION AGAINST TORTURE (CAT) PROTECTION Under the Convention Against Torture (CAT) and its implementing regulations (8 C.F.R. § 1208.16–18), removal must be withheld or deferred if it is more likely than not that the applicant would be tortured by or with the acquiescence of a public official in the country of removal. CAT protection is available regardless of criminal history bars that apply to asylum and withholding. WORK AUTHORIZATION Asylum applicants may apply for an Employment Authorization Document (EAD) (Form I-765) 150 days after filing a complete I-589. The EAD is issued 180 days after the asylum application was filed (the "asylum clock"). DHS action may stop the asylum

clock if the applicant fails to appear for scheduling or the application is incomplete. TRAVEL WHILE ASYLUM IS PENDING Asylum applicants should NOT travel outside the United States while their application is pending, as this may be deemed an abandonment of the application and may provide grounds for removal. DERIVATIVE ASYLUM A principal applicant who is granted asylum may include their spouse and unmarried children under 21 on the asylum grant as derivative asylees, if they were listed on the I-589 or a separate I-730 petition is filed. ADJUSTMENT TO LAWFUL PERMANENT RESIDENCE An asylee may apply for adjustment of status to lawful permanent residence (Form I-485) one year after being granted asylum. The applicant must have been physically present

in the US for one year after the grant of asylum and continue to meet eligibility requirements. KEY PRECEDENTS AND LEGAL STANDARDS Matter of Acosta, 19 I&N Dec. 211 (BIA 1985): Established the "ejusdem generis" rule for defining "particular social group." Members must share a common, immutable characteristic that they either cannot change or should not be required to change because it is fundamental to their individual identities or consciences. Matter of A-B-, 27 I&N Dec. 316 (A.G. 2018) and its reversal: The Biden administration issued guidance restoring asylum protections for survivors of domestic violence and gang violence, reversing restrictive interpretations. INS v. Cardoza-Fonseca, 480 U.S. 421 (1987): The Supreme Court established that the well-founded fear standard requires only a

reasonable possibility of persecution, not a probability. A 10% chance of persecution may satisfy the standard. USCIS AFFIRMATIVE ASYLUM PROCESS — TIMELINE - File I-589 → fingerprints biometrics → interview scheduled (currently 2-4+ years backlog) - 150 days after filing: may apply for work authorization - 180 days after filing: work authorization issued - Interview with asylum officer → approval or referral to immigration court DEFENSIVE ASYLUM — REMOVAL PROCEEDINGS TIMELINE - Detainees: cases prioritized; hearings may occur within weeks - Non-detainees: Master Calendar Hearing → Individual (Merits) Hearing (1-5+ years backlog) - After IJ denial: 30 days to appeal to BIA - After BIA denial: 30 days to petition for review to Circuit Court of Appeals - Stays of

removal may be requested pending appellate review FORM I-589 — KEY SECTIONS Part A: Biographical information Part B: Basis for claim (which grounds apply, narrative of persecution) Part C: Other information (prior applications, criminal history, etc.) Part D: Signature and attestation Supporting Documents: Identity documents, evidence of persecution, affidavits, country condition reports, medical or psychological evaluations, police reports LEGAL REPRESENTATION There is no right to government-appointed counsel in immigration proceedings. Applicants may be represented by: licensed attorneys, accredited representatives of recognized organizations, or law school clinical students under supervision. Many non-profit organizations provide free or low-cost immigration legal services to asylum seekers.
